    <h2 id="how-do-you-determine-the-right-pot-size">How Do You Determine the Right Pot Size?</h2>
    <p>
      Container size matters because it directly limits root development, and root development limits everything else the plant does above the soil line. A pot that&rsquo;s too small restricts roots before the plant reaches its potential, forces more frequent watering as the small soil volume dries out fast, and can leave a plant permanently stunted or root-bound. A pot that&rsquo;s too large has the opposite problem: roots can&rsquo;t draw water from all that extra soil fast enough, so it stays wet for days after watering, starving roots of oxygen and inviting root rot.
    </p>
    <figure class="my-6 float-right ml-6 w-48 sm:w-64">
      <img
        src="/pot-size-calculator-nesting-pots.svg"
        alt="A row of nursery pots in increasing sizes, from a small starter pot to a large gallon container"
        width="400"
        height="250"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-xl border border-moss-100 bg-moss-50/30"
      />
      <figcaption class="mt-2 text-xs text-bark-500">
        Size up gradually — the horticulture industry&rsquo;s own container ladder moves in small steps for a reason.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The right size, then, is the smallest container that comfortably fits the plant&rsquo;s <em>current</em> root system with a little room to grow into &mdash; not the size it will eventually need at full maturity. That&rsquo;s why repotting is a gradual, staged process (see the Repotting Size-Up mode above) rather than a one-time decision, and why the Container Size Guide below gives a <em>minimum</em> size for each plant&rsquo;s mature form rather than a size to start it in as a seedling.
    </p>
    <p>
      Depth matters as much as width for many plants. A wide, shallow pot and a narrow, tall pot can hold the same volume of soil but suit very different root structures &mdash; taprooted vegetables like carrots need depth, while shallow-rooted plants like lettuce and most succulents do better in a wider, shorter container.
    </p>

    <h2 id="pot-size-conversion-chart">Pot Size Conversion Chart</h2>
    <p>
      Standard nursery containers, sorted by diameter. The industry has no single enforced sizing standard, so treat these as typical figures rather than exact universal dimensions &mdash; always measure your actual pot if precision matters. Rows marked with an asterisk are estimated (small starter pots are conventionally sold by diameter only, with no rated volume).
    </p>

